proof:
For any two numbers $x$ and $y$, the expression $(x+y)(x-y)$ simplifies to $x^2-y^2$, since the terms $xy$ and $-xy$ cancel each other out. Using this fact, we can simplify the given expression as follows:

\begin{align*}
  \left( \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3} \right) &= \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2 - \left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^2\\
  &= \frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{9}\\
  &= \frac{9}{36} - \frac{4}{36}\\
  &= \frac{5}{36}
\end{align*} 

This confirms that the given expression equals $\frac{5}{36}$.
